<TITLE> Schools, colleges must have 40% female teachers: ministry </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Mustak Ahmed Dhaka, May 17 (bdnews24.com)All non-governmental schools, colleges, madrasas and vocational institutions in metropolitan cities and municipal areas will have to recruit at least 40 percent of female teachers, an education ministry order said on Sunday. Beyond metropolises and municipalities, the quota for female teachers will be 20 percent. Following the government decision is compulsory for all, except in 10 districts and 17 'remote' upazilas, it said.. Newly established educational institutions will lose their teaching permits, institutions waiting MPO listing will not be included and male teachers recruited in the female quota of an MPO-listed institution will not be given the MPO if the order was not complied with. Md Moyezuddin Ahmed, joint secretary at the education ministry, told bdnews24.com that the rule was relaxed for 10 districts until Dec 31 because there might not be enough female applicants. A second circular would be issued if no female candidate applies after the first circular, the order said. The third circular would be open for all, both male and female. The 10 districts are Sylhet, Moulavibazar, Sunamganj, Habiganj, Brahmanbaria, Kishoreganj, Netrokona, Rangamati, Bandarban and Khagrachhari. The 17 'remote' Upazilas are Monpura in Bhola, Sandwip in Chittagong, Meghna in Comilla, Kutubdia in Cox's Bazaar, Maheshkhali, Hatia in Noakhali, Kotalipara in Gopalganj, Doulatpur in Manikganj, Dhobaura in Mymensingh, Shoronkhola in Bagerhat, Dakop and Koyra in Khulna, Shyamnagar in Satkhira, Rajibpur and Roumari in Kurigram, Atrai in Naogaon and Chouhali in Sirajganj. bd
